If host port cannot be reused, how does Kubernetes allow multiple containers behind ONE port?
🧩 Problem Recap

In Docker:
Host:8080 → Container1:80
You cannot do:
Host:8080 → Container2:80 ❌

So how does Kubernetes expose:

myapp.com → 10 containers
on same port 80?

🚀 1️⃣ How Kubernetes Solves It — Using Services

Kubernetes introduces a new abstraction:

👉 Service
A Service:
Has a single stable IP
Has a single port
Forwards traffic to multiple Pods
Load balances automatically

🔹 Example Setup

You deploy 3 pods:
Pod1 → app container (port 80)
Pod2 → app container (port 80)
Pod3 → app container (port 80)

Now create a Service:

kind: Service
spec:
  type: ClusterIP
  ports:
    - port: 80
      targetPort: 80
  selector:
    app: myapp

Now:
ServiceIP:80
Forwards traffic to:
Pod1
Pod2
Pod3

🧠 Important

Service does NOT bind host port directly.
Instead it:

Uses iptables / IPVS rules
Distributes traffic to Pods
Works inside cluster network

2️⃣ How Kubernetes Exposes To Outside World

There are 3 main types:

Type	         Use Case
ClusterIP	   Internal only
NodePort	      Expose via node IP
LoadBalancer	Cloud external LB

🔥 2️⃣ How Kubernetes Exposes To Outside World

There are 3 main types:

Type	Use Case
ClusterIP	Internal only
NodePort	Expose via node IP
LoadBalancer	Cloud external LB

🔹 NodePort

Example:
NodeIP:30007 → Service → Pods
Still only ONE node port used.

🔹 LoadBalancer (Cloud)

In AWS / GCP / Azure:
Kubernetes asks cloud provider to create:
External Load Balancer
Public IP
That LB forwards traffic to nodes.

🌍 3️⃣ How Load Balancers Allow Multiple Containers Behind One Port

Let’s say:

www.myapp.com:80

Behind the scenes:

Load Balancer (port 80)
         │
         ▼
Kubernetes Service
         │
         ▼
Pod1
Pod2
Pod3
Pod4

Why this works?

Because:
Only Load Balancer binds port 80 publicly
Pods don’t bind host ports
Service distributes traffic internally

🧠 Key Difference from Docker

In plain Docker:
Host port → container port (direct binding)

In Kubernetes:
Host port NOT directly bound to pods
Service + proxy handles routing
Pods are not exposed individually

🔄 4️⃣ Real Traffic Flow Example (Cloud)

User → myapp.com

DNS resolves to Load Balancer IP
LB receives request on port 80
LB forwards to Node
Node forwards to Service
Service load balances to Pod
Pod responds
All behind one single public port

🎯 Kubernetes solves the host port limitation by introducing Services. A Service provides a stable IP and port and load balances traffic across multiple Pods.
Instead of binding host ports directly to containers, traffic flows through the Service abstraction.
When exposed externally using LoadBalancer type, a cloud load balancer receives traffic on one port and distributes it across multiple Pods internally.

🏆 One-Line Summary

Docker:
One host port → One container
Kubernetes:
One Service port → Many Pods
